    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Plotting Harmonic Oscillator Wavefunctions\n",
        "In this module we will plot Harmonic Oscillator wavefunctions. We will (hopefully) see the use of recursion relations. To get started, we will write some code that will plot a given Hermite polynomial **H$_n$(x)** as a function of x. One way to do this would be to have the code precalculate all possible Hermite polynomials and the use **if...then** logical statements to print the correct one. Look at the pseudo-code below for an example\n",
        "\n",
        "`if n==0:`\n",
        "\n",
        "`  f = 1`\n",
        "\n",
        "`elif n==1:`\n",
        "\n",
        "` f = 2*x`\n",
        "\n",
        "In this psuedo code, the user inputs a value for the quantum number `n`. If the value of `n` is `0`, `if n==0:`, then it sets the function to the 0$^{th}$ Hermite polynomial `f=1`. Else, if `n` is `1`, `elif n==1:`, then it sets the function to the 1$^{st}$ Hermite polynomial, `f=2*x`. The problem with coding this way should be clear. If the user wants to print out the 3$^{rd}$ Hermite polynomial, the code crashes. So, we should try to use recursion relations to make this code generalized. How can this work?\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Recall the recursion relation we learned in class: 2$\\gamma$H$_n$=H$_{n+1}$+2$n$H$_{n-1}$. This relation can be rewritten as H$_{n+1}$=2$\\gamma$H$_{n}$ $-$ 2$n$H$_{n-1}$\n",
        "2. This means if we precalculate H$_0$ and H$_1$, we can use recursion to calculate H$_2$. Once we calculate H$_2$, we can use recursion to calculate H$_3$. Once we know H$_3$, we can use recursion to ....\n",
        "3. So, we need to create a loop that loops through the recursion relations and ends at the Hermite polynomial we want to calculate.\n",
        "\n",
        "We will write this code in the **code chunk** below. If the line after a comment is blank, you will need to fill it in. If the line after a comment has code in it, I filled it in for you. If you forgot how to do things, look at your previous notebooks.\n",
        "\n",
        "Pay close attention. This code will introduce two new topics: `if/then` logic statements and multidimensional arrays, ie matrices instead of vectors!"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2GpE0rqhfZPD"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Add in a markdown title that automatically reruns the code when new parameters\n",
        "# are entered\n",
        "# @title #Plot a Hermite Polynomial { run: \"auto\" }\n",
        "# Load in NumPy\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "# Load in MatPlotLib\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "# Add in a markdown paramter, alpha, for alpha - recall that gamma = sqrt(alpha)*x\n",
        "#@markdown alpha\n",
        "alpha=1#@param{type:\"number\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "# Add in a markdown parameter, n, for the number associated with the hermite\n",
        "# polynomial you'd like to plot\n",
        "#@markdown Hermite Polynomial Number\n",
        "n=3#@param{type:\"number\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create an NumPy array called x that contains 200 evenly spaced values from\n",
        "#(-30/(2n+10)-1)*np.sqrt(2/alpha*(n+1/2)) to (30/(2n+10)+1)*np.sqrt(2/alpha*(n+1/2)).\n",
        "# These bounds were chosen so that the x-axis goes to at least the classical\n",
        "# turning points, +/- np.sqrt(2/alpha*(n+1/2)). These are your x-values, or x-axis.\n",
        "tp=np.sqrt(2/alpha*(n+1/2))\n",
        "xlim=(30/(2*n+10)+1)*tp\n",
        "x=np.linspace(-xlim,xlim,200)\n",
        "# Create an empty 2-dimensional array, H, that will store the hermite polynomials.\n",
        "#The first index is the number of polynomials you want to store (n+1), and the\n",
        "#second index is the total number of x-axis values (200)\n",
        "H=np.empty([n+1,200])\n",
        "# Create the 0th Hermite polynomial. H[0,:] = 1 means set all values of the\n",
        "#first row to 1, 0 means the first row and : means all the columns\n",
        "H[0,:] = 1\n",
        "# If the user selects a number greater than 0, you will need to create\n",
        "#the (1st Hermite polynomial)\n",
        "if n > 0:\n",
        "  # Create the first Hermite polynomial, The line starts with H[1,:] =\n",
        "  H[1,:]=2*np.sqrt(alpha)*x\n",
        "# If the user selects a number greater than 1, you will need to use recursion\n",
        "#relations and set up a loop\n",
        "if n > 1:\n",
        "# loop over range of Hermite polynomials needed. Use the variable i as an index.\n",
        "# Recall that we already have the the 0 and the 1 polynomial. To get the n=2\n",
        "# polynomial, we use recursion relations with the n=0 and n=1 polynomial.\n",
        "# We will loop from i=1, to i=n. Inside the loop we will calculate the (i+1)st polynomial\n",
        "  for i in range(1,n):\n",
        "    # Create the (i+1)st Hermite polynomial using recursion relations.\n",
        "    # The statement should start with H[v+1,:] =\n",
        "    H[i+1,:]=2*np.sqrt(alpha)*x*H[i,:]-2*(i)*H[i-1,:]\n",
        "# Plot x on the x-axis and the nth Hermite polynomial on the y-axis.\n",
        "plt.plot(x,H[n,:])\n",
        "# Set the x-limits of the plot. Plot from\n",
        "# -xlim to xlim\n",
        "plt.xlim(-xlim,xlim)\n",
        "# Give your plot a title. Make the font 16pt.\n",
        "plt.title(\"Hermite Polynomial\",fontsize=16)\n",
        "# Label the y-axis. Call it H_n(x), where n changes depending on what value you\n",
        "# want to plot\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"$H_%i$(x)\" %n,fontsize=16)\n",
        "# Label the x-axis with the Angstrom symbol.\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"($\\\\AA$)\",fontsize=16)\n",
        "# Show the plot\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "mtf9nnZugKIE"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Now, let's take the above code and turn it into what we really want, i.e. a program to plot a wavefunction for a given quantum number. This code will be similar to the last code, only you will calculate the wavefunction, $\\psi_n(x)=\\frac{1}{(2^n n\\ !)^{1/2}}(\\frac{\\alpha}{\\pi})^{1/4}e^{\\left(-\\alpha x^2/2\\right)}H_n(\\alpha^{1/2}x)$\n",
        "\n",
        "Hint: You will need to import the math package, `import math` and use `math.factorial(n)` to calculate $n!$ . `math.pi` or `constants.pi` (if you load in the scipy constants package) will work for $\\pi$."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "RSrn0w5AGP79"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Add in your code\n",
        "# @title #Plot a Harmonic Oscillator Wavefunction { run: \"auto\" }\n",
        "# Load in NumPy\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "# Load in MatPlotLib\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "# Load in math\n",
        "import math\n",
        "# Add in a markdown paramter, alpha, for alpha - recall that gamma = sqrt(alpha)*x\n",
        "#@markdown alpha\n",
        "alpha=1#@param{type:\"number\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "# Add in a markdown parameter, n, the quantum number\n",
        "#@markdown Quantum Number\n",
        "n=3#@param{type:\"number\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create an NumPy array called x that contains 200 evenly spaced values from\n",
        "#(-30/(2n+10)-1)*np.sqrt(2/alpha*(n+1/2)) to (30/(2n+10)+1)*np.sqrt(2/alpha*(n+1/2)).\n",
        "# These bounds were chosen so that the x-axis goes to at least the classical\n",
        "# turning points, +/- np.sqrt(2/alpha*(n+1/2)). These are your x-values, or x-axis.\n",
        "tp=np.sqrt(2/alpha*(n+1/2))\n",
        "xlim=(30/(2*n+10)+1)*tp\n",
        "x=np.linspace(-xlim,xlim,200)\n",
        "# Create an empty 2-dimensional array, H, that will store the hermite polynomials.\n",
        "#The first index is the number of polynomials you want to store (n+1), and the\n",
        "#second index is the total number of x-axis values (200)\n",
        "H=np.empty([n+1,200])\n",
        "# Create the 0th Hermite polynomial. H[0,:] = 1 means set all values of the\n",
        "#first row to 1, 0 means the first row and : means all the columns\n",
        "H[0,:] = 1\n",
        "# If the user selects a number greater than 0, you will need to create\n",
        "#the (1st Hermite polynomial)\n",
        "if n > 0:\n",
        "  # Create the first Hermite polynomial, The line starts with H[1,:] =\n",
        "  H[1,:]=2*np.sqrt(alpha)*x\n",
        "# If the user selects a number greater than 1, you will need to use recursion\n",
        "#relations and set up a loop\n",
        "if n > 1:\n",
        "# loop over range of Hermite polynomials needed. Use the variable i as an index.\n",
        "# Recall that we already have the the 0 and the 1 polynomial. To get the n=2\n",
        "# polynomial, we use recursion relations with the n=0 and n=1 polynomial.\n",
        "# We will loop from i=1, to i=n. Inside the loop we will calculate the (i+1)st polynomial\n",
        "  for i in range(1,n):\n",
        "    # Create the (i+1)st Hermite polynomial using recursion relations.\n",
        "    # The statement should start with H[v+1,:] =\n",
        "    H[i+1,:]=2*np.sqrt(alpha)*x*H[i,:]-2*(i)*H[i-1,:]\n",
        "#Calculate the wavefunction\n",
        "psi=np.sqrt(1/(2**n*math.factorial(n)))*(alpha/math.pi)**4*np.exp(-alpha*x**2/2)*H[n,:]\n",
        "# Plot x on the x-axis and the nth wavefunction on the y-axis.\n",
        "plt.plot(x,psi*psi)\n",
        "# Set the x-limits of the plot. Plot from\n",
        "# -xlim to xlim\n",
        "plt.xlim(-xlim,xlim)\n",
        "# Give your plot a title. Make the font 16pt.\n",
        "plt.title(\"Harmonic Oscillator Wavefunction\",fontsize=16)\n",
        "# Label the y-axis. Call it H_n(x), where n changes depending on what value you\n",
        "# want to plot\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"$\\\\psi_{%i}$(x)\" %n,fontsize=16)\n",
        "# Label the x-axis with the Angstrom symbol.\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"($\\\\AA$)\",fontsize=16)\n",
        "# Show the plot\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "G4eeo3SdGl_u"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
